	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98495207242441>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>RE: REPOST OF A VERY LONG MAGICIAN GUIDE</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Mar 18th 4:47 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Not a bad guide, but it leaves a few holes. In such a huge game environment, there really is no "one best" way or place to fight.<br><br>Toxxulia Forrest: It's really not such a bad newbie area, once you get used to it. It's certainly no worse than Nektolous Forrest or the Feerrot. One of your first purchases should be True North; this level 1 spell will point you towards the Erudin city entrance, and it's great for finding home again. At level 4, get Sense Summoned. There are three summoned NPC pets in the zone. Jalen Goldsinger's pet is right outside a caster supply hut where you can buy malachite and sell your goods at much better prices than any other merchant save your guild merchants. If you get one of the other two pets (Elial Brook's or Gnarthene Skurl), cast true north and run for your life. You don't want to mess with them.<br><br>You can partner up to take on the kobald camps for a level or two, then you can solo the camps and take on any skeletons that wander past. Your pet can solo the skunks, which occasionally drop a scent gland which sells for over 1 gp. The kobalds themselves drop hides, gems, boxes, bags, and booze. You'll have enough money to get your pet and a couple of auxilliary spells when you get to level 8.<br><br>At level 8, go pay Elial Brook a visit. You can easily solo him at this level with your improved pet, and he gives excellent faction; you can further improve faction by turning in his bones to Markus in the magician guild.<br><br>Once you've gotten your faction up to "warmly" with your guild, you can venture to The Warrens for some team dungeon fighting, or head to Erud's Crossing for good experience and loot at the same time.<br><br>Erud's Crossing: It's not just about the wisps. In fact, you'll get more consistant money and decent experience taking out the various kerran snakes and vampire bats you find. The snakes drop giant snake fangs and venom sacs, which sell for upwards of 3gp apiece, and tons of snake scales. The scales are near worthless as sellable loot, but you can give them or sell them to shamans (maybe in exchange for a buff or two), or you can use them to gain caster faction in Qeynos if you didn't start out there.<br><br>Vampire bats are usually a pretty easy fight, and they drop upwards of 3 wings/furs per bat (I've seen as many as five of each). They also drop jars of saliva, which sell for a decent price. The only ones to really watch for are the bats with skeleton pets; they will cast some nasty necromancer spells, and they are usually 3-5 levels higher than the other bats on the island.<br><br>You can handle most of the fire elementals that spawn on the island; these are lower level elementals than the ones at Lavastorm.<br><br>The occasionaly Island Madman will be excellent experience. You can solo them when they con yellow, although you should be careful because they are casters and they don't always stay focused on your pet.<br><br>Stay away from the spiders unless you have a death wish. They are very social and the island is small enough that you can attract the attention of a half dozen spiders very easily. Save the spiders for when you are level 16 or so and return to buy some new spells and get some guild training; you can handle multiple spiders at that point, and you can save up silk swatches for tailoring.<br><br>The wisps are good experience in their own right. Don't destroy the regular lightstones; they sell for about 8gp apiece. You can also take a money loss and turn them in along with greater lightstones for a little more experience. The burned-out lightstones are needed for practice research, but they are NO RENT so there is no need to keep them unless you are in your upper 20s.<br><br>In short, this island is about a lot more than just wisps. Most of the common mobs are good experience and excellent loot for their level. I fought from 8-12 in Erud's Crossing and had enough money for every single level 12 spell, with ALL of my greater-lightstone loot left over for future uses.<br><br>Lavastorm Mountains: I'm not sure why you disdain Lavastorm; it was built for magicians and druids. The loot is outstanding, and the experience is plentiful. Few mobs will aggro on you unless you start attacking, so it's a relatively safe place to fight. Summon up a couple of dimensional pockets to store those bricks of ore, and sell them in the zone so you don't have to carry them around. You don't have to return to a city until you run out of spell components or your small change starts weighing you down; Invisibility and a little caution will get you through Nek Forrest with little risk, and from there it's a short jaunt to Freeport. You can even buff up your shady Freeport faction in your early levels by doing the Slonsin quest in Erudin (if you started there). That quest raises lots of factions and lowers none.<br><br>Besides, Lavastorm is just such an awesome looking and sounding zone. Not to mention the higher levels who hang out at the various dungeon zones and who will often give you some really nice buffs for free. (You don't even have to ask; however, giving a few common drop bloodstones to a cleric will usually result in a good symbol spell for you).<br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
